1m6.title: Arbital Markdown questionnaire
1m6.clickbait: How to ask questions in Markdown.
1m6.text:
[summary: Arbital's questionnaire feature allows the author to create multiple choice questions that result in improving user's experience by modifying their known and wanted requisites.]

This feature is highly experimental, hard to use, and quite likely to break at any time. Please use with caution.

Each question has an alias associated with it. This alias only has meaning inside this page. (There is no overlap with page object aliases from other pages.) If you change the question significantly, please change the alias too. This will reset users' answers.

NOTE: Order of parameters is mandatory: knows, wants, -knows, -wants.

[multiple-choice(q1): What is the furthest page you've read?
a: I haven't read anything, but I want to!
wants: [1m9]
b: I've only read [1m7].
knows: [1m7]
wants: [1m9]
c: I read [1m8].
knows: [1m7],[1m8]
wants: [1m9]
d: I read all the way through [1m9].
knows: [1m7],[1m8],[1m9]
e: I don't want to read anything.
]

[multiple-choice(q2): Reset everything?
a: No.
b: RESET!
-knows: [1m7],[1m8],[1m9]
-wants: [1m7],[1m8],[1m9]
]

Arbital also supports checkboxes. (Default value is set by appending `!` to the answer option.)

[checkbox(checkboxAlias): Checkboxes are amazing!
y!:
path: [1lz],[1x5]
n:
]

### Paragraph conditionals

Nesting is supported by decreasing the number of `%`s for the nested conditionals.

%%%knows-requisite([1m7]):
%%!knows-requisite([1m8]):
Looks like you've only read [1m7], not bad.
%%
%%knows-requisite([1m8]):
%!knows-requisite([1m9]):Looks like you've read up to [1m8], very good!%  
%knows-requisite([1m9]): Wow, you've read everything!%
%%
%%%

%%!wants-requisite([1m9]): Looks like you don't want to read anything. That's OK!%%

%%wants-requisite([1m9]): [https://arbital.com/learn/1m9 Let's get started]!%%

### Span conditionals

These don't support nesting.

Example: Something you %knows-requisite([1m7]): probably remember from [1m7]:% %!knows-requisite([1m7]): might not know:% I like turtles!

### Path conditionals

You can check if a page will come before or after the current page in the path:

%!if-before([1m7]): [1m7] will NOT come later in the path%

%if-after([1m7]): [1m7] came earlier in the path%
